Analysis of Genre in Anime¶

Esteban Duran Sampdro

Introduction¶

Anime in japan is short for animation feature, so basically over there the word is used to reffer to any animated work, such as a Pixar film or a South Park episode. Conversly the term outside Japan is used to reffer to cartoons from Japan, particularly the ones with the big flashy eyes and extravagant hair styles. This isolation of the term in the"west" has downgraded the word to a genre, a mere format for children Shows.

However this scrutiny also points out what it really is, a medium for story telling, that happens to excel at fictional stories. More specifically an expancion to the animation feature medium set, as how the Japanese might see it as animations from home. The reason to call it an expancion, and not a subset (although an expancion it self is a sort of subset) is the variaty of genres in the anime, I mean there are more genres in anime than the traditional 'western' ones.

So from a set that tends to categorice its subsets into genres, then one can't create a subset that contains more genres than the original ones (disregarding combinations of the original ones), yet the desired subset might add to the different possible categories of genres, hense anime expands the animation feature story telling medium.

Before I loose myself in semantics, the point is that anime as an isolated story telling medium, is one that has shown great genre variety growth. The fact that anime shows high amount of surgances of new genres and/or combinations of them, and that it retains the attention of a huge fan community, inside or outside of Japan, is what's captivating from this source.

Moreover in a world more connected than ever, trends and inspirations flow faster and faster. Which means that studying a medium that shows high category variety of artistic expresion, it is worthy of study. As findings may help understand evolution of mediums of fiction, the apperance of anime trends and/or correlations with trends in other sources of fiction.

MyAnimeList is "the world's largest anime and manga database and community", whose users make list's of anime or manga(Japanese comics), are able to rate the shows, write reviews, and participate community forums. The kaggle data set, by user azathoth42, contains craweled data of MyanimeList, with information about different animes their different metrics (score, genre, popularity, release/broadcasting dates...), users demographics, and users lists (anime, score, status...).

This tutorial seeks to explore and analyze the "growth" of genre in anime over the years, and some of the metrics that may help understand the perception of these genres and different changes.

Data Washing¶

We will brush up the data in the anime table first.

We can remove several columns from the table due to redundancy or uselessness of the data in the context of analysing genre.

  • title_english, title_japanese, title_synonyms and background may be removed as the title column is enough string representations of the anime.
  • airing, aired_string, aired, premiered, and broadcast since air_from_year is enough information about the temporal origin of the show.
  • producer and licensor, may be removed as studio provides sufficient information regarding the make of the anime. And since studio variable probably have higher impact on genre than the producer or licensor. As one may consider studio the artit's house, wheras the others more of the money/resources houses.
  • opening_theme and ending theme may be removed, as those are simply the intro and outro song names, with image_url. As these columns bear no useful relevance to this analisis.
  • finnally related is removed as each value has the form of a data dictionary, that tends to point to a manga_id value from MyAnimeList, or an anime_id, and since the manga data is not available, this column has no usefulness for this tutotial.

The source atribute, describes the inspiration the story and/or style of the anime, such as a book or game. Looking at the possible sources categories, using the unique function on the 'source' column of the anime dataframe, makes me wish there were more detail on the 'Game' and 'Other' lables. As Japan has a history of producing shows in order to promote material from other products in japan, ie card games, toys, video games. Hence the desire of the divition of games into video and non video games, and if possible the divition of other into toys, food or candy, all of which might show more understanding on the apperance of new genres in anime (Sorry for the impertinence MAL, you're an awesome site). Also there are few sources that are too similar, if not a subset format, of the manga source. So those sources may be repleaced simply by manga. Furthermore the Visual novel, novel and light novel source shouldn't be considered as a single source since they are truly different from one another; one refers to novels in prints, novel; other to novels with pictures, light novel; and the other one to novel told with pictures in a video game, visual novel. They might still sound similar but they are distinguished enough to have different influence in genre.

From the type column the rows with the lable music may be removed as such format is more related to the music medium vs the story telling one. I don't mean to say that music can't tell a story, just that it's not it's forte. Also the type OVA stands for original video anime, and ONA original net animeation, basically animes that wer not released in tv, movie, or special format, but where released inpendently online or in tape, just to provide a description of these.

From the different durations of anime one might notice some have lenght under a minute, which reading around those animes make reference to sub/hidden stories within other animes, that is just too specific and there is no need to include those in the analisis. So they get removed by escluding rows that have the string "sec. " which is unique for animes under a minute.

Also removing the animes that have status not yet aired, since some of the metrics wouldn't bare a relistic or stable value, such as a score or popularity.

From the genre column, the animes that have no genre value are removed since this tutorial has focuse genre, furthermore there are only 2 animes that lack genre in the data.

Also since years are integer values, changing the vlaue of aired_from_year to an int might be usful, or more clean.

All of this data cleaning is done below. And the data frame after brushing up is shown below.

In [134]:
#removal of columns
animedf.drop(['title_english', 'title_japanese', 'title_synonyms',
              'image_url','airing', 'aired_string', 'aired', 'background', 
              'premiered', 'broadcast', 'related', 'producer', 'licensor', 
              'opening_theme', 'ending_theme'], axis=1, inplace=True)

#replacing sources similar to manga, with manga
animedf['source'] = animedf['source'].replace(['4-koma manga', 'Web manga', 'Digital manga'], 'Manga')

#removing lines with type music
animedf = animedf[animedf['type'] != 'Music']

#removing animes with duration under a minute
animedf = animedf[~animedf['duration'].str.contains("sec.")]

#removing animes that haven't aired
animedf = animedf[animedf['status'] != 'Not yet aired']

#removing animes without genre value
animedf = animedf[pd.notnull(animedf['genre'])]

#chageing the data typr of aired_from_year from double to int
animedf['aired_from_year']=animedf['aired_from_year'].astype(int)

animedf = animedf.reset_index(drop=True)

The genre atribute that has the form of a list of genres per anime requires special attention. So in order to unfold this sublists within each anime 43 different columns, one per genre, would be added to the data frame; if an anime has that genre in it, it will contain a 1, 0 otherwise.

Below is the code to add the columns in the data frame. With code to collect a list of each anime genres as a list, which will be useful later on.

Now we clean the users list data.

Some columns from this table may be removed as well

  • my_start_date, my_finish_date, are too user specific, also the lack of values in some columns such as finish date would make it dificult to find a data relevant for genre such as mean time lapse speed to complete a specific genre show.
  • my_rewatching_ep is too redundant on the my_rewatching, it is enough to now if a user deems the anime valuable enough to rewatch, but not the number of episodes. also there was some user that claimed it had rewatched a lewd anime for more than thousands of years. So getting rid of internet troll data is good too.
  • my_watched_episodes is not relevant for this genre analysis as simply knowing that the user was interested in an anime of zed genre, regardles of the amount of episodes watched will suffice.
  • my_last_update and my_tags are irrelevant for this analisis, as the last time the show was updated by user dosnt matter and the tags vary too much, often unique for a show and/or user.

The my_rewatching column contain either 1s, 0s or null values, so filling the null values with zeros would tidy this pice of data.

Some username values are null, so this would be dificult to define the null user a single one, morover when there could be overlap of rows with nullfor user and same anime_id. So removing the rows for the null users.

The status atributes possible values are described as follow: 1, watching; 2, completed; 3, on hold; 4, dropped; 6, plan to watch. But within the possible values found there are also 5, 55, 0 and 33. As 5, 55 and 0 are not a status with any meanig they are removed, and the 33 varaible will be interpreted as a typo and replaced with a 3.

Below is the code to do this data washing, with a print of the cleaned data frame.

In [136]:
#deliting columns from user anime list data frame
anime_listsdf.drop(['my_watched_episodes', 'my_start_date', 'my_finish_date', 'my_last_updated', 'my_rewatching_ep', 'my_tags'], axis=1, inplace = True)

#replacing null with zeros

Looking at the data per anime in a whole graph reveals how deficult it is to analize some values look at the valus individually per anime. So it is time to look at these values some kind of aggregate. Sinse genre is the focuse of this tutorial, the below code is to make a new dataframe that contains the different genre as rows, and as columns the years that the anime table span. This is a nicer way to group the values per genre than some awkward group by a list of all the genre columns. I learned the method below to unpack from a calumn values that have the shape of a list of strings, in this kaggle tutorial, by Kevin Mario Gerard, of an analysis on a movie dataset. This method is used throughout the tutorial. Furthermore the resulting dataframe helps view and understand the data better, at least the growth of each genre per year.

In [143]:
#getting min and max year values, t define column values
min_year = animedf['aired_from_year'].min()
max_year = animedf['aired_from_year'].max()

#define data frame with range of years as column values and genres as rows
anime_genredf = pd.DataFrame(index = genres, columns = range(min_year, max_year+1))

#filling the data frame with zeros
anime_genredf = anime_genredf.fillna(value = 0)

#getting an array of the years of individual animes
year = np.array(animedf['aired_from_year'])
y = 0

#dictionary to collect number of different genres in total
genre_count = {}

#for loop to iterate through the list of genres per anime
for g in anime_genres_set:
    
    #split the anime's genre into a list
    split_genre = list(map(str, g.split(', ')))
    
    #iterate through the genres's of the anime
    for gs in split_genre:
        
        #add count for that genre in that year in the dataframe
        anime_genredf.loc[gs, year[y]] = anime_genredf.loc[gs, year[y]] + 1
        
        #count the dictionary
        if gs in genre_count:
            genre_count[gs] = genre_count[gs] + 1
        else:
             genre_count[gs] = 1
    y+=1

In [207]:
genres_pop=[]
genres_score=[]
genres_mem=[]

#collecting special lables for each new data frame
for g in genres:
    g_pop = g + ' popularity'
    g_score = g + ' score'
    g_mem = g + ' members'
    genres_pop.append(g_pop)
    genres_score.append(g_score)
    genres_mem.append(g_mem)
    
anime_popdf = pd.DataFrame(index = genres_pop, columns = range(min_year, max_year+1))
anime_popdf = anime_popdf.fillna(value = 0.0)
anime_pop = np.array(animedf['popularity'])
pop_count = {}

anime_scoredf = pd.DataFrame(index = genres_score, columns = range(min_year, max_year+1))
anime_scoredf = anime_scoredf.fillna(value = 0.0)
anime_score = np.array(animedf['score'])
score_count = {}

anime_memdf = pd.DataFrame(index = genres_mem, columns = range(min_year, max_year+1))
anime_memdf = anime_memdf.fillna(value = 0.0)
anime_mem = np.array(animedf['members'])
mem_count = {}

y=0
for g in anime_genres_set:
    split_genre = list(map(str, g.split(', ')))
    for gs in split_genre:
        anime_popdf.loc[gs+' popularity', year[y]] = anime_popdf.loc[gs+' popularity', year[y]] + anime_pop[y]
        anime_scoredf.loc[gs+ ' score', year[y]] = anime_scoredf.loc[gs+ ' score', year[y]] + anime_score[y]
        anime_memdf.loc[gs+ ' members', year[y]] = anime_memdf.loc[gs+ ' members', year[y]] + anime_mem[y]
        if gs+' popularity' in pop_count:
            pop_count[gs+' popularity'] = pop_count[gs+' popularity'] + anime_pop[y]
            score_count[gs+' score'] = score_count[gs+' score'] + anime_score[y]
            mem_count[gs+' members'] = mem_count[gs+' members'] + anime_mem[y]
        else:
            pop_count[gs+' popularity'] = anime_pop[y]
            score_count[gs+' score'] = anime_score[y]
            mem_count[gs+' members'] = anime_mem[y]
    y+=1
    
#standardizing the score and popularity data frames as those values refelct a quality metric rather than a quantitative one
anime_popdf2 = (anime_popdf - anime_popdf.mean()) / anime_popdf.std(ddof = 0)
anime_scoredf2 = (anime_scoredf - anime_scoredf.mean()) / anime_scoredf.std(ddof = 0)

#averaging the count of the scores of the popularity and score by the tottal number of animes in each genre in the data set
for g in genres:
    score_count[g+' score'] = score_count[g+' score']/genre_count[g]

Data folding¶

In this section you'll find the implementation of a machine learning model, the Random Forest Classifier, using an scikit-learn library. The model is a random generation of deisions trees to determain animes by their genres, that averages them out out to predict the anime genres. The model then will be tested using the data based from the anime list of a user in the user anime list table. Bellow you'll find the code necessary to collect the required data to build the model.

#Make a pandas series object containing the sum of animes per year from the anime data frame
#this will be used as the target values for the model
year = np.array(animedf['aired_from_year'])
years = range(min_year, max_year+1)

for y in years:
    year_count[str(y)] = 0
for y in year:
    if str(y) in year_count:
        year_count[str(y)] = year_count[str(y)] + 1
year_counts = pd.Series(year_count)

Bellow you'll find the code that makes the model. The model uses the the transpose of the anime genres by year frequency data drame as the X input, so the genres are the columns/atributes are the genres, and the rows/entries are the years. The target values are total anime by year. This model uses by default the gini index criteria, which basically takes the most probable value to atribute that will decide the calissification of the object, in this case the differnt genres. This model uses 10 estimators by default, that is to say it generates 10 trees to average out Then there is some code to print relrevance of each anime to determine an animes genres.

Data wearing¶

To wrapp up this tutorial let me say that eventhough the tutorial was attempeted to be divide by data cleaning, exploration and analisis sections, the tutorial throughout showed compenets of previous sections. This reflects how the process of analysing data, has no linear progress, but oftes requires stepping back to previous stages of analisys. This is not seen in the last stage of this tutorial, that is because there is more to explore in the model, as there is more to explore in any other stage. During each stage there were several lines of questioning about the data left un-answered in general to clean, analyse, understand and/or run models on. The data could be set up to add the variables as more atributes for the model, such as genre per score, or genre per popularity. Or maybe even look for more atributes whose exploration might suggest better candidacy to include in the model... All this is to say that this tutorial if anything has also inspired me to understand ways of exploring data and be able to apply the learned value of data.

Furthemore I shared some fun facts about anime through out the tutorial, for those curious about the subject here are a couple of anime youtube channels that cover several topics explored here. But may mane recomendation is to simply watch some anime.
